items.name: Beautiful Mistake
items.description:
What you are getting here, is a business level's TI, for free.

This TI was actually trained for a head pose, but failed. It not only learned a head pose, but also learned this face into it.

Those images used for training, are all AI generated Asian super star with a business model trained by professional. 20 male images and 20 female images are used here.

But somehow, this trained TI just merges all those faces into this one super cute girl.

Since this TI is failed and that pose I need is re-trained into a Lora, so I'm sharing this TI, now you can have this super cute girl for free.

Version Differences:

number is the training steps.

5500: Less problem on details, but also less background

6500: Better background and lighting, but more chance having issues on details

8500: Even better lighting, less issue on character, but more chance having background issue.

SFW and NSFW

Those images for training only have head, no body at all. so, if you have NSFW issue, that is a problem with your model. Just adjust your prompt.

Model

This TI is trained with SD 1.5 base model. But tested with Basil.

(Basil is the base of ChilloutMix)

Prompt

"masterpiece, best quality" are used for training, you better have them too.

Most examples uses following prompt:

Prompt:

beautiful_mistake-YourVersionNumber, a beautiful girl, 1 girl, medium close shot, upperbody shot, dark hair, brown eyes, looking at viewer, no smile, high detail, intricate detail, best quality, masterpiece, (photorealistic:1.2)

Negative prompt:

(worst quality, low quality:1.2)

modelVersions.description: 6500: Better background and lighting, but more chance having issues on details than 5500
8500: Even Better lighting, less issue on character, but more chance having background issue.

items.name: Pant Pull Down - LoRA
items.description:
Important: Having multiple models uploaded here on civitai has made it difficult for me to respond to each and every comment. One of the ways I plan on addressing this is via the creation of a pdf guide for each and every model (think of it as the models documentation). This will take a while though. So in the meantime, if you have any questions or feedback -

visit my thread of the Unstable Diffusion Discord

Similar to shirtlift butt for booty lovers.

Admittedly, this was just made for fun. It's not as versatile as shirtlift, as trying find good data was quite difficult. In the end, the model was trained on roughly 100 pictures. Manual tagging + BLIP were used for captions.

General Prompt Guide

  • Simply add pantpulldown towards the end of your prompt, followed by <lora:pantpulldown:1>

  • Add "rear view" angles towards the beginning of the prompt: rear angle, from behind, viewed from behind, back towards viewer, ect..

  • Noting the butt size somewhere in the prompt can also help: big butt seems to work well, but can sometimes force closeup shots.

  • Adding full body towards the beginning is useful for full body shots. (note, this may be different depending on what SD model you use).

  • For short length prompts setting the weight between 0.5 and 0.8 seems be optimal: <lora:pantpulldown:0.6>

  • Conversely, For longer length prompts setting the weight to 0.8 and 1 seems to optimal: <lora:pantpulldown:1>

  • Describing whether or not genitals are exposed can help elevate issues where genitals are not generated properly, or are visible when you prefer they not be.

  • Interestingly, I've had the best results by adding the LoRA at the end of full length prompts; as show in most of the sample images.

Issues

  • Bad faces

    • Try adding "pretty face" to your positive prompt.

  • Bad hands

    • Hands are the devil for Diffusion models; try adding "perfect hands" to your positive prompt, and "mutated hands, distorted hands", ect.. to your negative prompt.

  • Bare bottom with no pants

    • Increase the LoRA weight in your prompt.

Realistically, A hypernetwork + still frames of people undressing their pants would likely be ideal. This is something I'll consider after I finish training my upcoming "Enhanced skin texture" hypernetwork.

items.name: Muv-Luv's style armors
items.description:
=== V2 ===

The trigger is still fortified suit, BUT the second recommended tag isn't bodysuit anymore, it's plugsuit with the color you want. For example: ((blue:1.5) plugsuit)

The sweet-spot is still between 0.6 and 0.7. "Animal ears" issue in the previous version is fixed but not heterochromia (unfortunately I don't even know how to fix that) so keep "heterochromia" in your negative.

Males are way easier to generate, it's not perfect but you don't need to go crazy with the weights anymore. The armor as a whole is also more consistent and you shouldn't find missing parts on your gens.

The dataset was a bit too contaminated by the pink colored armor from Sumika. So you still need to add more weight to all your colors (unless you like pink). I'll try to fix that in the next version.

This version should work well with realistic models and any artstyle (feel free to test and report here if you encounter an issue).

=============================

Not made for realism! It only works for anime style.

It's my first LoRA so I think it's not up to the standard yet. Anyway, it produces muv-luv armors which I couldn't get with any model or prompt (that's how niche it is).

You use it by adding "fortified suit" tag in your prompt and I recommand adding "bodysuit" tag as well. The sweet-spot for this LoRA seems to be between 0.6 and 0.7 for the weight.

It has been trained on 126 images (official arts and fanarts), it's very biaised against males since males are only 20% at most of the dataset! Although, if you put a very high weight like (1boy:1.9) and (1girl:1.3) in negative you still can get some guys.

There are a few issues with heterochromia and animal ears, so put these in negative if you don't want that in your art.

To change the color of the armor you can write something like (blue:1.5 and fortified suit), (black:1.5 and bodysuit).

Other related Muv-luv stuff (robots): https://civitai.com/models/8584/muv-luv-tsf-concept-lora

modelVersions.name: v2.0
modelVersions.description:
The trigger is still "fortified suit" (with the space) BUT the "bodysuit" tag was replaced with "plugsuit". You use it like the previous tag, so for example it's "((blue:1.5) plugsuit)" instead of "((blue:1.5) bodysuit)"

Improved:

  • Size reduced to 36Mb with no loss in quality.

  • Generation of males is way easier (you don't need to crank up the weights anymore) and more consistant colors for the bodysuit.

  • Breats size is much more adjustable, you can make flat chested girls easily (and without turning them into males).

  • Fixed the animal ears issue on girls.

  • Should work well with realistic models and way more flexible with any artstyle. However, high weights (>0.85) will still affect the style.

  • Full body shot and complex poses are more easily generated. The whole armor (gloves, boots, mouthpiece...) is treated as an item so you shouldn't get missing parts of the armor on your gens.

To be improved:

  • Issue with a helmet added on males (due to one male wearing a helmet in the dataset), so put "helmet" in your negatives.

  • Inconsistent body types with males. You can get skinny males or bodybuilder-tier males at random. You can use the "skinny" tag to fix that.

  • Some details (on the navel mostly) are still inconsistant. Heterochromia is still an issue (easily solved by putting "(heterochromia:1.2)" in your negatives)

  • Too many Sumika in the dataset, by default it'll try to prompt the pink bodysuit so put some weight on your colors like "((blue:1.5) plugsuit)". Hopefully, that'll be fixed in the next version.

items.name: Rika (Pokemon) LoRA
items.description:
I just finished beating Pokemon: Scarlet today and decided to make Rika.

This is a LoRA for Rika from Pokemon.

I suggest using this LoRA at 0.9-1.0 weight for best results.

These Images were generated with AbyssOrangeMix3_A1 and OrangeMix VAE. This was trained on the NAI Model and only tested on AOM3 and Corneo's 7th Mix.

I used on Hires. fix on all of the pictures using these settings - I'm not sure if they're the best so if you have any suggestions for Hires! Leave them in the comments!

R-ESRGAN 4x+ Anime6B, Upscaled by 1.25, Hires. Steps - 0 and Denoising at 0.1

Small Fixes (Optional)

You can add these tags to help it generate a little better but it's entirely optional, if you wish to save tokens.

items.description:
This is a cool little merge project. Does really well in SFW haven't done any NSFW testing but should be just fine.

There are 2 different models with different baked VAEs. They are both great and work well, but feel free to test them out and find which you like the most!

I recommend using Euler a, as the DPM ++ samplers tend to mess with the faces. You can totally fix this with a little inpainting as the rest of the images look totally fine.

IMPORTANT:

To properly generate furry characters, I highly suggest adding the tags:

"|species| |gender| furry", "anthro", "fursona", "anthropomorphic", "(|color| fur)".

Just put whatever species, gender, color, etc. you want. Without these the model tends to do more anime and monstergirl type gens. The fur color helps prevent skin color being human and it just brings a solid and more fur like color and texture to the images.

This model does require some inpainting to get what you want.

items.name: Alizee Jacotey (2000s)
items.description:
Alizée Lyonnet (née Jacotey) is a French singer who rose into stardom in the early 2000s.

Update: The TI has been updated after a 2-star review complaining about its oversaturation. Granted, version 1.0 was indeed oversaturated, but that was easily fixable by simply reducing the weight of the TI a little bit. Did it deserve a 2-star review just for that, basically ignoring any other merits? I very much doubt so, but to each their own, I guess. It's pushed me to create a new version of this TI, which was one of my first. It probably was about time anyway.

Appreciate my work? My TIs are free, but you can always buy me a coffee. :)

Curious about my work process? I have summarized it here.

How to create a good prompt using my TIs

You're obviously free to experiment, but bear in mind that my TIs are trained with a more or less fixed phrasing, that normally starts with:

"photo of EMBEDDING_NAME, a woman"

So I recommend always starting your prompt like that and then building the rest of the prompt from there. For instance, "photo of (alizjacot:0.99), a woman, RAW, close portrait photo, long brown coat, turtleneck sweater, pale skin, slim body, (high detailed skin:1.2), 8k uhd, dslr, soft lighting, high quality, film grain, Fujifilm XT3 sharp focus, f 5.6".

items.name: Aoi Odisann Style LoRA
items.description:
Aoi Odisann Style LoRA

If you enjoy my models and want to support me you could buy me a coffee!

This LoRA mimics the artstyle of the artist Aoi Odisann. Keep in mind when using it that it was trained on 6GB VRAM so the embedding might not be as good as other ones on this website but you can still get satisfactory results.

The example images were created with AbyssOrangeMix2 and I was using varying weight but feel free to experiment with different weights and models. It's a bit similar to my ORIHARA LoRA but it seems slightly more attuned to making men. I tried briefly to mix it with a couple of different embeddings and it didn't give the best of results but you might find a better way to mix them (changing different weights etc.).

To change the weight just change the '1' in this prompt: <lora:Aoi-Odisann:1>.

I'd love to see the art you guys make with it so feel free to add them in comments.

How to use LoRA's in auto1111:

  • Update webui (use git pull like here or redownload it)

  • Copy the file to stable-diffusion-webui/models/lora

  • Select your LoRA like in this video

  • Make sure to change the weight (by default it's :1 which is usually too high)
